· PREFACE

Tms edition is intended to enable the student to under- stand and interpret the Laelius. Enough elementary

matter has been introduced to adapt it for use in the best , preparatory schools‚ and enough advanced matter for the

first year of college. There are repetitions of statement and numerous cross-references, in which the teacher of experience will recognize the wellestablished pedagogical principle that facts are not impressed by being stated but once.

The notes are full, -especially on the subjects in which students are generally deficient. There has been a con- stant effort on the part of the editor to train the student to observe for himself certain peculiarities in the language which are characteristic not only of the Laelius but of all classical Latin.

Acknowledgment is made in the notes of the material taken from other commentaries Those of Reid, Strelitz, and Monet were most frequently consulted.
